|   Because *JSPlotly* involves a programming language, *JavaScript*, it is plausible that it can offer a set of operations tangible to it, independently of building graphs (as in diagrams and flowcharts above).

|   In parallel to the richness that accompanies *gamification* as an active methodology, the *creation of a game* can stimulate the learner to another level, since strategy is sometimes already part of their daily life. Playing is one thing...creating a game can have a more prominent and recursive impact on computational thinking and logic, as well as on learning the programming language itself!

### Memory Game

#### BNCC: EF06MA19, EF06MA16, EF07MA26, EF09MA19, EM13MAT401, EM13MAT102, EM13MAT403, EM13LGG701 {.unnumbered}

|   The clickable image below directs to a classic *Numeric Memory Game*. The objective is to hit a pair of values after memorizing a numeric grid. To play, follow the instructions below:
\

**Instructions for the Numeric Memory Game:**

* 1. In the upper field there are two boolean constants true/false, one to play (*jogue*) and another to check correctness (*verificar*), as well as a *seed* that fixes a certain random numeric grid;
* 2. Start the game (*jogue/false*, *verificar/false*);
* 3. Click the *add* button and a grid of numeric pairs for memorization will be displayed;
* 4. Switch to *jogue/true*, click *clean plot*, and then *add*. The grid will now be displayed with only one value (other cells will show *"?"*);
* 6. Choose *verificar/true*, click *clean plot*, and then *add*. A field will be presented to type the coordinates where you believe the other numeric pair is (Ex: A2);
* 7. Click *OK*, and a pair formed by the initial value and the chosen value will be presented, to verify correctness.

|   To restart the game, *clean plot*, and boolean options *false*.

|   Have fun!!
\

[![](Eq/game.png)](Eq/jsp_game2.html){target="_blank"}


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
1. To play again changing the grid values, just change the *seed* constant to any number;
2. To vary between difficulty levels of the game, just change the number of rows and columns in the respective code constants. 
```
:::


